# Memory budgeting (Cursor + Bob)

Treat the context window as a fixed budget (~200K). Squad target: **stay under ~60%** on active ticket chats.

## Four buckets

| Bucket | What belongs | Examples |
|--------|----------------|----------|
| **A - Fixed** | Always needed | Active ticket id, 4-gate checklist, orchestrator rules |
| **B - Session** | This chat only | ticket-spec.yaml, files you are editing, last Bob PASS/FAIL summary |
| **C - On demand** | Fetch when needed | One processor YAML, one DB verify query, `bob query-graph` slice |
| **D - Never** | Out of chat | Full repo @, unrelated `docs/tdd-runs/`, Gradle/boot logs, old tickets |

## Agent habits

- **One ticket per chat.** Archive when switching tickets (`bob chat-hygiene --auto`).
- **Pin sparingly:** ticket-spec + 1-2 files max.
- **Bob proof stays in files:** read `GATE_SUMMARY.md` / `REPORT.md` paths; summarize in ~5 lines, do not paste logs.
- **Start heavy work fresh:** if context feels full, new chat + `docs/tdd-runs/<id>/TICKET_RESUME.md`.
- **Run once per ticket:** `bob context --ticket <id>` - link paths, do not dump the whole CONTEXT_PACK.

## Session status

If `{workspace}/.cursor/memory-budget-status.json` shows `"status": "critical"` or `"warn"`, prefer a **new chat** before large edits and run `bob memory-budget`.

## Commands

`bob memory-budget` · `bob context-audit` · `bob chat-hygiene --auto` · `bob prune-overhead --apply`
